ovh6DXdFeBN03_u8iSepXqsGPu97Bv4BmcGlzrwHLuUDQqwf79l7eab2slPMAFeCZPZQC6b1sgX=
DJ-UjHiTQ1G1tu4U_oG8O3gbA] likely helped grease the wheels. As with Marketp=
lace in Thailand, as Facebook works out the kinks in India, it will roll ou=
t messaging-based payments to its 3.2 billion MAPs around the globe as it s=
lowly convinces governments it can be trusted with our money.
As it continues to connect its various platforms and integrate more commerc=
e and payments functionality, Facebook will complete the most ambitious bac=
kward integration in history, from ads into eCommerce. It will own the funn=
el.=C2=A0
To be sure, all of this is early and unproven, and Facebook isn=E2=80=99t e=
xactly known for its product innovation. For a unification project, it all =
feels a bit piecemeal. Plus, the company has also faced headwinds in market=
s around the globe, where governments are slow to trust Facebook to handle =
payments. But it points to how Facebook is thinking about unifying its prod=
ucts to help businesses not only reach, but communicate with and sell direc=
tly to, new and existing customers, wherever they happen to be.=C2=A0
To that end, it=E2=80=99s not hard to imagine that Facebook might even roll=
 out Shops and messaging functionality through its mobile app ad network, F=
acebook Audience Network [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuhDAM_JrN=
rSgxgYVDDr30N1Ae3t0ISFDiFNGvb2BVVbJkayzPeMZqwmdMh9piJlYypsk7JXoY2k6OzCnpxNA=
NzOfpkRBX7RdFqSDbilm81eRjuC44h4691MDvvbQ93DVKLZ0bjQUrRmux1bobR3bqTLo4j8Giwm=
9MRwzIFvUi2vKt_bzBV61935uHtmhinBsb1wqZkn3AnOsYcD_bH81HQNpjmplXwIELEFK0Xd-Oj=
Wig-MfP3Drj3U3y9QlNLiaTthctSypEMjH58Kzr-aVXXK5F9TfVvpbg6ZgwaLOge1und1iXEzo2=
VOc7CxJheoM1D-gAet7fWVVzscYW_oV-AZfagMc]. The implications of that would be=
 enormous. It would mean businesses will be able to set up =E2=80=A6 shop =
=E2=80=A6 anywhere they=E2=80=99re able to place ads today. Imagine checkin=
g out directly in ads across the internet; see, click, buy, or talk to a pe=
rson (or AI) to answer any questions. If Facebook pulls off that vision, it=
 will have its own Everywhere Store to battle Amazon=E2=80=99s Everything S=
tore.=C2=A0
Oh yeah, and one more thing=E2=80=A6=C2=A0
Facebook=E2=80=99s Next Reality
Everything that Facebook has achieved on mobile is made more impressive by =
the fact that Facebook almost missed the platform altogether. It was a desk=
top-first product when it went public, and the market didn=E2=80=99t believ=
e it could make the transition to mobile. The app was janky and built on HT=
ML5 (RIP), and analysts feared that a mobile NewsFeed couldn=E2=80=99t supp=
ort an ad load. Its shares fell from $42 to $19 in Facebook=E2=80=99s first=
 three months as a public company.
Zuck fixed the mobile problem by acquiring Instagram and pushing the compan=
y into a hard pivot, but it was harrowing, and he vowed to not miss the nex=
t one. To that end, Facebook made two acquisitions that are particularly in=
triguing:=C2=A0
Oculus. Acquired the maker of VR headsets for $2.3 billion in 2014.=C2=A0
CTRL-labs. In a less splashy move, acquired the brain-computing startup for=
 between $500 million and $1 billion in 2019.=C2=A0=C2=A0
As of August, Facebook rolled Oculus, CTRL-labs, Portal, and Snap Lens Stud=
io lookalike Spark AR into Facebook Reality Labs [https://email.mg2.substac=
k.com/c/eJxFUMGOhSAM_Bo5GgH14YHDXt5vGJCiRAQDZTfu1y9PD5s0aaaTznS6KIQ1pkueMSM=
pGdLsjKQjE3zoJ2Jkb6gYBHF5tgngUM5LTAXIWbR3i0IXw73RdWwgmxzti4Omyi4j5ZpTO4leaG=
EHKyZmJkM-PrMqxkFYQMI3pCsGIF5uiGdu-FfD3rWUjgVbq9slHhUmUN7h5ZXOFREnWcc6ymhP-=
TDyqaUtK87-7txoZ5q-O1bW5qIzqmX_SJAkQ0QdkwtrpfdNHeBvouaYaz9KqPozBKU9mCciPk-5=
L8brBBngJ3tAhPQMa242MDZ244tUNxPre8K_0R8_g3dQ]. The division, reporting to A=
ndrew =E2=80=98Boz=E2=80=99 Bosworth, is responsible for Facebook=E2=80=99s=
 efforts in VR, AR, and the spatial computing operating system. With its ha=
nds tied on social and messaging acquisitions, eight of its last ten acquis=
itions [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFULtuwzAM_JpoNCTZcp1BQ5dM_QdBEm=
mHsC25ejRwv75KMhQgcCAP5PHO24JLTKc-Yi6sZkyGQItRTr0argz0AGJSE6Ns5oS4W9p0SRXZU=
d1G3haK4bXBuVTsrkdQMKqJ4-Rcz7nn8wBqhEG42XnHBXvqGFuBMHjU-IPpjAHZpu-lHPnSf17k=
rRWG7kErHQhku5iWNnr2Db6oHYiz2TEtmLKxAYz135UyPZ_Jxp3mZj26GFdGWnLJhRSD6NXYXzv=
RyUrz79qDI7gMfF9kl6vLxfq183FnSYdYXEwUlkavd7vj9iKaYdNwr4HKaTBYtyG8syjv9F7Wyn=
mgDvjIG5aC6T1sAUkl5cjHD9bUILYcw7_QHzLRiAE] have been under Facebook Reality=
 Labs. It=E2=80=99s easy to dismiss the effort -- who wants Facebook contro=
lling the Metaverse? -- but it=E2=80=99s showing potential.=C2=A0
Portal. After a chilly reception that went something like =E2=80=9Cno fucki=
ng way am I letting Zuck into my house,=E2=80=9D Portal sales have taken of=
f during the pandemic. My sister lives in Ghana, and she and my mom talk ov=
er Portal every day. When we=E2=80=99re all physically distanced, the Porta=
l can make people feel closer together.=C2=A0
Oculus. Facebook lowered the price point for the Oculus Quest 2, it=E2=80=
=99s newest VR headset, to $299, and pre-orders surpassed the original Ocul=
us=E2=80=99 by 5x. Oculus Quest 2 is the best standalone headset on the mar=
ket, and is likely to be the best-selling of all-time.
Spark AR. While this is a painfully blatant rip off of Snap, the same logic=
 I used for Snap holds here: by putting lightweight AR in hundreds of milli=
ons of peoples=E2=80=99 hands, Facebook is getting an early headstart on bu=
ilding Mirrorworld.
AR Glasses. Facebook has plans to release AR glasses next year, in partners=
hip with Luxottica. Early attempts to build AR glasses -- from Google Glass=
 to Snap Lenses -- have ranged from butt-of-joke to toy-like, but if Facebo=
ok can marry what=E2=80=99s worked in Oculus with the lighter touch needed =
for AR, it has a shot.=C2=A0
Just like Facebook=E2=80=99s social apps, the Facebook Reality Labs product=
s will work together, in this case to try to usher in the era of spatial co=
mputing on Zuck=E2=80=99s terms. To become the platform, Zuck predicts the =
company needs to sell 10 million Oculus headsets in order to attract enough=
 developers to build an ecosystem. That=E2=80=99s why the company dropped i=
ts price to $299.=C2=A0
The prize couldn=E2=80=99t be bigger: if Facebook becomes the default platf=
orm for VR, AR, or both, it will hold the position that Apple and Google ho=
ld in mobile today. Plus, it will be able to plug in its social, messaging,=
 and commerce features to the new platform from day one, creating new oppor=
tunities for businesses, and of course, for Facebook itself.=C2=A0
Is Facebook owning a foundational Metaverse platform a good thing? Probably=
 not. Over the past two weeks, I finally read Ernest Cline=E2=80=99s 2012 M=
etaverse instant classic, Ready Player One [https://email.mg2.substack.com/=
c/eJxFkMtqxDAMRb9mvEvwK06y8KKUdtvSHwh2rMyYOHbwoyHz9fXMLApCgnsRVzqzynAN8ZR7S=
BmVBHGyRhJBB9bxERnJDRm6Adk0LRFgU9bJHAugvWhnZ5Vt8M8NjGmHbnKcsQHMlVhGvRiGORZa=
9FQQM_SCMY0eOZMqxoKfQcIvxDN4QE7ect7Thb1d6Get4zhatal78O0ctir8gDJn8-3UCbH58tB=
8RA8pN-_Oeqi-2WvDDPfD0HNeD5YUU0wo4YR1go0taWmxy31lRltz4Xi70jYVnbKa10cGitKHrE=
O0_lrt9aY2cE-jvjrVuRVv8zmBV9qBeVHIL27Pp_K5g_RwJAc5Q3yJFQ3tKBVY9KimmVAJ-v-gP=
7eUgVk], and his new sequel, Ready Player Two [https://email.mg2.substack.c=
om/c/eJxFkMtqxDAMRb9mvEvwI3aShReltOtSug92rMyYOHbwoyHz9fXMLApCgnsRVzqzynAN8Z=
R7SBmVBHGyRhJBB8a7ERnZGTLwAdk0LRFgU9bJHAugvWhnZ5Vt8M8NjClHNyn6gS-m13wZseoFx=
npWYtFsZEJwMmL0yJlUMRb8DBJ-IZ7BA3LylvOeLuztQj9rHcfRqk3dg2_nsFXhG5Q5my-nTojN=
